x4freetext: -Excitation functions of threshold reactions
on Sc-45 and Mn-55 induced by 6 to 13 MeV neutrons.
The Julich CV28 variable-energy compact
cyclotron delivered deuteron beams in the energy range
4 - 10 MeV, giving neutrons in the 6.3 to 12.85 MeV
range.
Zero-degree neutrons from the d + d reac-
tion were used. The mean neutron flux ranged between
.Quasi-monoenergetic.
Gamma counters were used to measure induced
activity. Low level beta- counting was applied for
Ca-45 and Cr-55.
No info on which was used for which data.
.Sc2O3 and Mn02 powder, > 99.9%, was pressed
into 1.3 cm diameter x 0.35 cm thick pellets. Mn02,
100 mg, was filled into a 1.3 cm diam x 3.1 cm
polyethylene tube. Aluminium and iron monitor foils,
200 mg/cm2, were attached at the front and the back
of the samples.
For the low-level beta counting, a thin chemically
separated Ca-45 sample was prepared, by dissolving the
Sc2O3 sample in HCl and CaCl2 carrier was added to it.
Sc(OH)3 was precipitated and centrifuged off. then
calcium was precipitated as oxalate, which was
converted to CaCO3 by heating at 500 C.
From IRDF.
From IRDF.
The neutron flux was monitored via the Fe-56(n,p)
reaction over the neutron energy range 6-8 MeV, and
the Al-27(n,a) reaction between 8 and 13 MeV.
.The beta data were corrected for V-52 interfering
decay. This was achieved by measuring its gamma
activity. Corrections for background neutrons (target
in-vs-out) and breakup neutrons were applied.
Total errors includes:
Correlated:
Error in excitation function of
monitor reaction
uncertainty in decay data
Uncorrelated:
uncertainty in sample weight
uncertainty in irradiation time
uncertainty in irradiation geometry and beam
deviation
Statistical error
